131: Australia recognizes Auslan, also known as Australian Sign Language, as a national language of the deaf community, but not an official language
Austria recognizes Österreichische Gebärdensprache, or Austrian Sign Language, as a recognized minority language

Belgium has three officially recognized sign languages: Vlaamse Gebarentaal, also known as Flemish Sign Language in Flanders, Langue des Signes de Belgique Francophone, also known as Francophone Belgian Sign Language in Wallonia, and Langage Gestuel de Belgique Germanophone, also known as German-Belgian Sign Language in the German-speaking community
Brazil recognizes Libras, or Brazilian Sign Language, as an official language alongside Portuguese

Canada has two officially recognized sign languages: American Sign Language, used primarily by English-speaking Canadians, and Langue des Signes Québécoise, used primarily by French-speaking Canadians in Quebec
Chile recognizes Lenguaje de Señas Chileno, also known as Chilean Sign Language, as an official language
Costa Rica recognizes Lengua de Señas Costarricense, or Costa Rican Sign Language, as a recognized minority language
Denmark has two officially recognized sign languages: Dansk tegnsprog, also known as Danish Sign Language, and Døves tegnsprog, which is the original name used by the deaf community in Denmark
Finland recognizes Suomalainen viittomakieli, or Finnish Sign Language, as an official minority language
France does not have a single recognized sign language but several regional ones including Langue des Signes Française, or French Sign Language, and has proposed its recognition in several regions

Germany has three officially recognized sign languages: Deutsche Gebärdensprache, also known as German Sign Language, Französische Gebärdensprache, used primarily by the French-speaking population near the border with France, and Österreichische Gebärdensprache, which is used in some areas of Bavaria
Hungary recognizes Magyar jelnyelv, or Hungarian Sign Language, as a recognized minority language
Iceland has not officially recognized Íslenskt táknmál, also known as Icelandic Sign Language, however it is widely accepted and taught in schools
India does not recognize any sign language at the national level but some regional ones are used like Bharatiya Sanketa Lipi or Indian Sign Language
Ireland recognizes Irish Sign Language, also known as ISL, as a recognized minority language
Italy has officially recognized Lingua dei Segni Italiana, or Italian Sign Language since 2021 and it is used alongside the official Italian language in some contexts
Japan does not recognize any sign language at the national level but Nihon Shuwa, also known as Japanese Sign Language, is widely accepted and taught in schools
Luxembourg recognizes Langue des Signes Luxembourgeoise, or Luxembourgish Sign Language, as a recognized minority language
Malta has officially recognized Lingwi tas-Sinjali Maltija, or Maltese Sign Language since 2016 alongside the official languages of English and Maltese
Mexico does not recognize any sign language at the national level but some regional ones are used like Lengua de Señas Mexicana, also known as Mexican Sign Language
Netherlands recognizes Nederlandse Gebarentaal, also known as Dutch Sign Language, as a recognized minority language
New Zealand has officially recognized New Zealand Sign Language, or NZSL since 2006 alongside the official languages of English and Maori
Norway recognizes Norsk tegnspråk, also known as Norwegian Sign Language, as an official minority language
Philippines does not recognize any sign language at the national level but some regional ones are used like Filipino Sign Language
Poland has officially recognized Polski Język Migowy, or Polish Sign Language since 1995 and it is used alongside the official Polish language in some contexts
Portugal recognizes Língua Gestual Portuguesa, also known as Portuguese Sign Language, as a recognized minority language
Russia does not recognize any sign language at the national level but some regional ones are used like Russkiy Zhestovy Yazyk or Russian Sign Language
Slovenia has officially recognized Slovenski znakovni jezik, or Slovenian Sign Language since 2011 alongside the official Slovene language
South Africa recognizes all eleven official languages including South African Sign Language as a twelfth language

Spain recognizes four sign languages: Lengua de Señas Española, also known as Spanish Sign Language, used primarily in most regions of mainland Spain, Llengua de Signes Catalana, or Catalan Sign Language, used primarily by the deaf community in Catalonia and some adjacent areas, Euskal Herriko Gainerako Zeinu Hizkuntza, also known as Basque Sign Language, used primarily in some parts of the autonomous communities of the Basque Country and Navarre, and Lengua de Señas Valenciana, or Valencian Sign Language, which is proposed to be recognized by the Generalitat Valenciana
Sweden recognizes Svenskt teckenspråk, also known as Swedish Sign Language, as an official minority language

Switzerland has four officially recognized sign languages: Langue des Signes Suisse Romande, used primarily in the French-speaking regions of western Switzerland, Deutschschweizer Gebärdensprache, used primarily in German-speaking regions of northern and eastern Switzerland, Lingua dei Segni della Svizzera Italiana, used primarily by the deaf community in some areas of southern Switzerland near Italy, and Langue des Signes Suisse Allemande

United Kingdom has two officially recognized sign languages: British Sign Language, or BSL in England and Northern Ireland, and Makaton is a simplified communication method using symbols for people with learning disabilities or other needs, as well as having the Welsh Government recognizing Cymraeg Canolradd, or North Wales Welsh Sign Language and Cymraeg De-orllewin, or South West Welsh sign language.
